er\\n\\nProfNet\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n PR Newswire Distribution Helpline\\n888-776-0942\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nTerms of Use\\nPrivacy Policy\\nInformation Security Policy\\nSite Map\\nRSS\\nCookie Settings\\n\\n\\n\\nCopyright \\u00a9 2024\\u00a0Cision\\u00a0US Inc.\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\",\n        \"type\": \"Document\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"lc\": 1,\n      \"type\": \"constructor\",\n      \"id\": [\n        \"langchain\",\n        \"schema\",\n        \"document\",\n        \"Document\"\n      ],\n      \"kwargs\": {\n        \"metadata\": {\n          \"source\": \"https://tvnewscheck.com/tech/article/local-tv-widens-embrace-of-virtual-sets-ar-vr/\",\n          \"title\": \"Local TV Stations Widen Their Embrace Of Virtual Sets, AR & VR - TV News Check\",\n          \"language\": \"en-US\"\n        },\n        \"page_content\": \"\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nLocal TV Stations Widen Their Embrace Of Virtual Sets, AR & VR - TV News Check\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n \\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n Skip to main content Skip to header right navigation Skip to site footer\\nMembers\\nJobs\\nEvents\\nLogin\\n\\n\\n\\nMenu\\nTV News CheckBroadcast Industry News - Television, Cable, On-demandHeader SearchSearch siteSubmit searchProgramming\\nTech\\nBusiness\\nAI\\nJournalism\\nDigital\\nRegulation\\nPeople\\nsearchSearch siteSubmit search\\n\\nProgramming\\nTech\\nBusiness\\nAI\\nJournalism\\nDigital\\nRegulation\\nPeople\\nsearchSearch siteSubmit search\\n\\n\\nMembers\\nJobs\\nEvents\\nLogin\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nHome \\u00bb Local TV Stations Widen Their Embrace Of Virtual Sets, AR & VRTechnologyTVN TechLocal TV Stations Widen Their Embrace Of Virtual Sets, AR & VR\\nJul 11, 2024 | Glen Dickson | Add commentFacebookTweetCBS-owned KPIX, Hearst\\u2019s WCVB and a growing number of TelevisaUnivision stations are among those leaning into virtual sets and expanding use of AR and VR elements, their tech leaders told a TVNewsCheck webinar last week.\\n\\n\\nThe best reason for news broadcasters to invest in new technology is to tell better stories. Augmented reality graphics and virtual sets have long held that promise, but historically local call-letter stations have found the technology to either be too difficult to implement or not realistic enough to viewers to get significant traction. That mindset is quickly changing, however, due to significant improvements in the realism of AR graphics and virtual environments, including both green screen and LED-based sets, as well as better integration with legacy production workflows.\\nThe improved usability of AR/VR for everyday news and sports production was the key takeaway from \\u201cVirtual Sets, AR and the News,\\u201d a recent TVNewsCheck webinar moderated by this reporter (watch it here). Top broadcast engineers and AR/VR software and hardware vendors described how the technology is being used on a regular basis by both local stations and national networks.\\nSolid Weather Forecast For VR At KPIX\\nKPIX, the CBS owned-and-operation station in San Francisco, has been using a virtual set for weather presentations in its daily newscasts since last September. The virtual set, which runs on Zero Density software and Epic Games\\u2019 Unreal Engine rendering, relies on a spacious green-screen background that curves onto a green floor, both painted with special ChromaLight paint. It allows KPIX meteorologists to walk across a 3D topographical model of San Francisco Bay and clearly depict the oft-stark differences in weather conditions between different parts of the greater Bay Area, which has roughly 15 microclimates, said Jeff Jeandheur,\\u00a0KPIX director of broadcast operations and engineering.\\n\\n\\n\\n\\u201cIt became a really unique way to bring the weather story into a new volumetric environment,\\u201d Jeandheur said. \\u201cWe started it with the evening primetime show and it very quickly made its way into all of our newscasts, and that\\u2019s how we\\u2019ve been doing it since last September.\\u201d\\nKPIX meteorologists run the virtual set through a touchscreen interface on an iPad, with an WSI controller on the flip side of it that they use to pull up AR graphics like a seven-day forecast that appears in a series of clear tubes. The meteorologists can also trigger more traditional weather graphics like weather maps, which appear in virtual LED monitors.\\n\\u201cThey\\u2019re driving all of that,\\u201d Jeandheur said. \\u201cFrom the control room standpoint, it was really just taking a different source, which was the output of our Zero Density system that composited everything.\\u201d\\nThe virtual set has proven reliable and surprisingly easy to use, he added, and as such its use has occasionally spread to other segments in KPIX newscasts. A particularly compelling example was using the virtual set to illustrate the proposed raising of the San Francisco Ferry Terminal by seven feet to address rising sea levels due to climate change. Another was displaying immersive 360 video for a story on California\\u2019s Redwoods forest.\\nThe set has also been used for special coverage of the Grammys and the 2024 Super Bowl, as well as four hours of live coverage of the March 5 political primaries. Jeandheur said that new virtual environments for those shows were able to be created in less than a week, and sometimes within a matter of hours.\\n\\u201cYou can paint it faster and render the story faster than you can paint a real set,\\u201d he said.\\nLate last month, the KPIX virtual set took to the national stage with the launch of a new \\u201cwhip-around\\u201d show on CBS News 24/7, CBS\\u2019s streaming network, which covers breaking news from around the world. CBS is using the KPIX set for the 1 p.m. ET edition of the show, also called CBS News 24/7, with a 10 a.m. ET edition originating from another virtual set in New York.\\nThe new show features a virtual wall of video in the background that is continually being fed by the CBS network and CBS affiliates. The hosts, Vladimar Duthiers in New York and Reed Cowan in San Francisco, stand on the virtual floor and pop in and out of stories by pointing to a feed on the wall, which then cues a switch to a live feed.\\nA New Look At WCVB\\nHearst Television\\u2019s ABC affiliate WCVB Boston updated its flagship Chronicle, the longest-running locally produced newsmagazine show in the U.S., this past January with the launch of its own virtual set. The green-screen environment, which has a similar curved wall-into-floor configuration as KPIX, uses Pixotope software with Unreal Engine rendering and set design from Devlin Design Group.\\n\\n\\n\\nSince its 1982 debut Chronicle has always been on the cutting edge of technology, said Kevin Kalia, WCVB director of engineering, including first producing in HD back in 1999. When WCVB was seeking to enhance the program, using a virtual set to replace a hard set dating back to 2007 was attractive, even though the station didn\\u2019t have any previous VR experience.\\n\\u201cIt gave us the opportunity to do something that we wouldn\\u2019t be able to do with a physical set at all,\\u201d Kalia said. \\u201cIf you watch our program, it looks like a very large space, we have multiple storytelling locations within the virtual set. The textures, the lighting, all of these things would be very difficult if not impossible to pull off, not just in our studio but probably in most studios around the country. It\\u2019s been very successful, and it\\u2019s been well received by our audience.\\u201d\\nKalia said that virtual sets \\u201caren\\u2019t quite plug-and-play yet,\\u201d and so the WCVB engineering and production staffs spent several months last fall working with vendors to iron out technical details including optimizing its rendering engines, inputting camera tracking data and integrating live video feeds. It also played around with different finishes to cut down reflections from its anchor desk, the one \\u201chard-set\\u201d piece in the new space.\\n\\u201cWe spent a couple of weeks, maybe even a couple of months, fine-tuning our rendering engines and working on optimizing the set model,\\u201d Kalia said. \\u201cBecause now we\\u2019re working in Unreal, as I think most of us are, and it\\u2019s not just a matter of what you see is what you get. You have to make it work in a way that it\\u2019s going to perform across the rendering platform. You have to build it with an eye towards efficiency and make sure it looks the way you want it to look.\\u201d\\nMaking AR/VR Easier\\nThe three biggest areas of improvement in virtual set technology are camera tracking; higher-performance, standardized rendering; and tighter workflow integration with legacy systems like graphics and production automation, said Mike Paquin, senior product manager, virtual solutions, Ross Video.\\n\\n\\n\\nIn terms of being able to use virtual sets for everyday news production, tracking is perhaps the most crucial.\\n\\u201cIf you go back 10, 15 years, a lot of the headaches that people remember in doing tracking in a virtual set was that you had to calibrate almost every show,\\u201d Paquin said. \\u201cIf you lost power, if you had to move a camera, all of a sudden you had to recalibrate, you couldn\\u2019t do a show that day. Now all of that tracking is either done with optical tracking, so the markers in the ceiling [such as Mo-Sys\\u2019 StarTracker], or with the robotics, they\\u2019re all absolute. So, when you power it on, even if you turn it off and move it, when it comes back on it\\u2019s all still in relative space, so there\\u2019s no recalibration. You\\u2019re not going to be stuck without doing it.\\u201d\\nMost virtual set vendors, including Ross, are using Unreal Engine today to create photorealistic graphics. Paquin said that standardization has also made implementation much easier compared to the early days of virtual sets, when each vendor used its own rendering engine with its unique quirks and limitations. Adopting Unreal has also provided broadcasters with a large labor pool of graphic artists that have honed their skills in other industries, such as architectural design.\\nBut Unreal still needs to be customized somewhat to make it perform efficiently for broadcasters, he added, which is a task that Ross has taken on for its customers.\\n\\u201cWhat we do is we help broadcasters essentially pare down the engine,\\u201d he said. \\u201cIt\\u2019s a super-powerful engine, it\\u2019s built to do gaming and all sorts of interactions, but there are a lot of things you have to do for performance. You have to build it for live production, so bringing in live inputs, bringing in the data integration, the weather stats. We build the tools to help do that, making it easy to use every day, not just something you want to do on a film set or something you spend months and months building and use it once.\\u201d\\nMaking it easy includes building tools for MOS integration, which allows Ross\\u2019 Voyageur virtual set to tie into Ross OverDrive for automated production control or integrate with Ross or third-party graphics systems. Ross has also integrated tracking for its robotic camera systems, Paquin said. All of that workflow integration means that stations no longer need a dedicated team of people to simply operate the set.\\n\\u201cNow the tools are there so you can integrate it with your switchers or your other graphics systems and make it so it can be used every day, and you don\\u2019t need to have a small team of people that that\\u2019s all they do,\\u201d he said.\\nVirtual Learning For TelevisaUnivision\\nOne broadcaster that Ross is currently working with on virtual set implementation is TelevisaUnivision, which operates a 20-station group in the U.S. [Univision Local Media] along with a bevy of broadcast and cable networks across the U.S. and Mexico. TelevisaUnivision was looking to use AR and VR to improve local news production at its stations, including the \\u201cability to dynamically change fast,\\u201d said Ruben Robledo, TelevisaUnivision SVP production operations.\\nWhile TelevisaUnivision\\u2019s sports properties regularly use green-screen virtual sets today, the local stations had only scant experience with AR and none with virtual sets. So, Robledo and the TelevisaUnivision projects team set up a proof-of-concept (POC) at the company\\u2019s San Antonio station to learn on the fly.\\n\\n\\n\\n\\u201cWe went to San Antonio and built it, and we got very good learnings,\\u201d Robledo said. \\u201cOne of them was that it didn\\u2019t change a lot from the control room back for us, which is kind of weird. I was expecting something different, but it was not. At the end of the day, the camera sees a studio. But there are changes for the people in the studio, the anchors, the people trying to position themselves in this environment that doesn\\u2019t exist. So that was really, really good for us.\\u201d\\nAfter successfully doing test productions over several months in San Antonio, Robledo is now overseeing the construction of a green-screen virtual set at its station in Phoenix as part of a comprehensive technical upgrade of that station. He hopes to replicate the model across the rest of the group in the future.\\n\\u201cWe\\u2019re in the middle of it, and hopefully this is the first one of many more to come,\\u201d Robledo said.\\nNew Opportunities With LED\\nWhile the broadcasters on the panel were all using green-screen virtual sets, networks like ESPN and Eurosport are employing walls of high-quality LED monitors as virtual backgrounds, noted David Jorba, VP of business development, Disguise. While LEDs have higher upfront implementation costs than green screens, Jorba said LEDs are easier to use and provide greater versatility for a range of production applications.\\n\\n\\n\\nThat includes the ability to create a parallax effect with virtual graphics shown on a large LED display, as ESPN does with the \\u201cdepth wall\\u201d on its hard set for SportsCenter, or to bring in live video feeds to facilitate face-to-face interviews with remote guests. Jorba thinks LEDs should be more seriously considered by local stations who are exploring VR.\\nDisguise also works with green screen environments, with customers including NBC as well as TelevisaUnivision\\u2019s sports networks. But Jorba said that making sure talent\\u2019s hair and clothing looks good, as well as their lighting, can be difficult when chroma-keying in a green screen environment. And a green-screen set can only support virtual or chroma-key applications, while LEDs can be used in a variety of ways.\\n\\u201cThe Disguise systems control the lighting, the camera tracking, the LED processors,\\u201d Jorba said. \\u201cThey\\u2019re controlling the whole environment, so you can program the system to go from one set to another by just pressing a button. That means in the morning you can do a show with just video playback and image playback as with the traditional LEDs you all have in your stations. Then in the middle of the day you can bring some augmented reality to it to do some storytelling, then later on you can do parallax like we do with SportsCenter. And then at night you can do a full XR [extended reality] set.\\u201d\\nTechnology\\nAbout Glen Dickson\\n\\nGlen Dickson has over 25 years of experience working in the media industry, most of it spent writing about the technology behind broadcast and cable television. He is currently a contributing editor to TVNewsCheck and a freelance writer for several publications. He previously served as senior editor of the Broadcasting & Cable, where he led its technology coverage as well as related podcasts, seminars and conferences. Dickson has served as a speaker at major industry conventions including the Consumer Electronics Show and NAB Show and also worked as an investor relations consultant to media and technology companies. He holds a B.A. in English from the University of Pennsylvania. Follow him on X: @GlenDickson\\n\\nView Posts\\n\\n\\n\\nReader Interactions \\nLeave a Reply Cancel reply\\nYou must be a logged in member to post a comment.Log In Register Now \\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nRelated Stories\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nFrance T\\u00e9l\\u00e9visions to Cover Paris Olympics Surfing Competition With Haivision\\u2019s Private 5G Video Transmission Ecosystem\\n\\nFrance T\\u00e9l\\u00e9visions will be providing coverage of the pre- and post-competition activities of the surfing event at the Paris 2024 Olympic Games. In partnership with Haivision, a provider of live \\u2026\\n\\nRead moreFrance T\\u00e9l\\u00e9visions to Cover Paris Olympics Surfing Competition With Haivision\\u2019s Private 5G Video Transmission Ecosystem\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nVizrt Focuses On BroadcastAV Market With PTZ3 Plus Cameras\\n\\nVizrt, a provider of real-time graphics and live production solutions for content creators, brings the BroadcastAV market sharply into focus with the launch of the PTZ3 Plus and PTZ3 UHD \\u2026\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nIBC: LiveU Celebrates 18th\\u00a0Birthday With Dedicated Lightweight Sports Production Solution & Tech Enhancements\\n\\nIn celebration of its 18 years, LiveU is set to unveil its \\u201cradically efficient and nimble cloud live production solutions and a range of new tech advancements\\u201d at IBC 2024 \\u2026\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nZTransform Recruits Broadcast Industry Veteran To Bolster Engineering Team\\n\\nZTransform, a technology solutions provider serving the broadcast, sports venue, corporate new media, education and government sectors, has appointed Reed Wilson senior design engineer. With more than \\u2026\\n\\n\\n\\n\\n\\nIBC: Cinegy Bringing Cloud M